T1  - Pollution: Can the People Be Innocent While Their Systems are Guilty?
AU  - Frew, David R.
Y1  - 1973/09/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255016
DO  - 10.5465/255016
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 527
EP  - 530
VL  - 16
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses the basic relationship between the concepts of organizational behavior and environmental pollution. Interviews with employees of a business organization known for pollution showed that all members of a business organization are opposed to the pollution their company was generating. Pollution emerged as a prime example of the random nature of inter-organizational behavior. Thus, it might be expected that some of the activities of organizations would be of negative social value. While members of organizations may be opposed to how the organization is behaving, the systems themselves continue to pollute.
AB  - The article discusses the basic relationship between the concepts of organizational behavior and environmental pollution. Interviews with employees of a business organization known for pollution showed that all members of a business organization are opposed to the pollution their company was generating. Pollution emerged as a prime example of the random nature of inter-organizational behavior. Thus, it might be expected that some of the activities of organizations would be of negative social value. While members of organizations may be opposed to how the organization is behaving, the systems themselves continue to pollute.
SN  - 0001-4273
